metadata.name: Deep Forest #173
metadata.description:
I love being in nature and impressionistic paintings. Deep Forest is my latest attempt to combine them with JavaScript. The editions will range from open, sparse forests to lush, dense, leafy wonderlands. Fall editions may render as Klimpt-style birch forests - my original inspiration for this work.

Best viewed on a computer. It may take a few seconds to start drawing and, depending on complexity, several minutes to finish rendering. In live view, press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2318x3000px.

Features:
- One of the four seasons
- Rare 10% night version with 50/50 for normal fireflies or "fire" fireflies. Night will only be spring or summer.
- Amount of atmosphere/haze
- Horizon line near the middle or 30% "high horizon" near the top
- Tint from one of 8 light and 7 shadow colors
- Strength of the light and shadow color tint
- Mixed tree trunks or 30% all birch
- 50/50 moss on tree trunks
- One of 8 flower colors in spring or summer
- One of 4 perspective transforms
- Straight, curved out, or 30% curved inward trunks
- 50/50 grass in fall or winter
- 85% will have flowers in spring and summer
- 95% will have underbrush
- 50/50 clouds or solid background
- 50/50 solid background will be vertical or swirls
- Ground hill height

metadata.name: Circumscript #187
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.

metadata.name: Trust #132
metadata.description:
Trust is an abstraction of the creative process, finding the line just before form becomes texture. Your experience with the painting requires trust; trust that something will appear from the chaos of the empty space, trust that the composition you imagine halfway through will evolve along with your ideas, and trust that the etchings lend a helping hand to the message of the piece. You may find yourself pulled left and right when decisions are made, and your interpretation at 25%, 50%, and 90% will all differ. This is what makes creating so fulfilling to me, a work of art can change course wildly from start to finish, ever molding itself until it enters the kiln.

Press ‘1’, ‘2’, or  ‘3’ to increase resolution (default is 1, higher than default may not work on certain browsers. Successfully testing in Chrome, Brave, and Opera GX with hardware acceleration enabled)

Click or tap to zoom to full res (exact zoom depends on your display)
Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle brush texture

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: MOUNTAINS #188
metadata.description:
"MOUNTAINS" is a work that belongs to the "FLUX Series", which utilizes the same techniques and processes as the previous work "FLUX". The shape in this piece is created by placing elements using noise and then performing recursive pixel operations on these elements.

The inspiration behind this work came from my continued sketches and studies of Flow Field, which led me to discover an expression of objects that seemed to be corroding. I believed that by applying this technique, I could create a realistic and vivid sculpture from a geometric shape.In this work, this corrosion treatment is applied to a geometric triangular shape of overlapping rectangles to form a realistic and dynamic mountain landscape.
It was as if geometric figures like Plato's "ideas" were materialized in the real world.

Additionally,  I was also inspired by the mountain views from my hometown at New Year's and by the manga background paintings of Yoshiharu Tsuge, who specializes in depicting villages with old hot springs.

It is possible to get a 5760 x 3240 px png file by right click save.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any inquiries.

Artwork by hasaqui, @hasaqui.
Made with p5js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Element #143
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Eucalyptus and Sagebrush #2
metadata.description:
Eucalyptus and Sagebrush is inspired by the eucalyptus trees and sagebrush found in California. These plants, and the hills they inhabit, have long been a source of beauty and adventure in my life, and I find myself repeatedly drawn back to them. The sunsets in coastal California are a perfect compliment to these hills, and I set out to represent that combination in this work.

Each iteration of this algorithm feels, to me, like a glimpse out of a car window on a drive up the coast, a pause on a cool morning hike, or a memory of tearing through sharp underbrush with good company.

Stylistically and texturally, I drew from landscapes rendered in oil pastels, placing thousands of tiny circles, alluding to the effect of depositing particles of color onto paper. 

I hope that this work evokes in the viewer the feelings of peace, wildness, and adventure that I feel when I watch the sun set over these hills.

Nat Sarkissian


Notes:
- Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

metadata.name: play/plaque #349
metadata.description:
A grid of trailing shapes. Each shape in the line wants to be like the shape in front of it.

The traits
4 shapes: square, cross, triangle, circle
5 grid sizes 1->5 with 1x1 grids being rarest (5%)
2 fill styles: hollow (80%, crosses can't be hollow) and filled (20%)
20% chance for all shapes to be the same
6 color palettes:
- Coffee and Blueberry
- Tropicana
- Monochrome
- Spectrum
- Peach and Pear
- Goji and Kelp

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao)
